Q: Does it ever make sense to allow copies but no moves? A: <p>Perhaps you are overthinking this. Just because you don't know how to implement moves does not imply that you should disallow move semantics altogether. If your class cannot be moved it is sufficient to fall back to copies:</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;

struct foo {
    int f = 0;
    foo() = default;
    foo(const foo&amp; other) : f(other.f) { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;copy\n&quot;; }
};

int main() {
    foo f;
    foo g = std::move(f); // prints: copy
}
</code></pre>
<blockquote>
<p>C++ Core Guideline C.64 suggests that a moved-from handle object whose t_ is equal to nullptr is fine</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It actually says:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Ideally, that moved-from should be the default value of the type. Ensure that unless there is an exceptionally good reason not to.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It is unclear to my why the authors push so much for the default value. Anyhow, not having a default value (you say there is no default constructor), is an exceptionally good reason to not try to make a moved-from state equal the default value.</p>
<p>The moved-from object is supposed to be in a valid but otherwise unspecified state. From that perspective, either <code>other.t_ = nullptr;</code> or not doing it is both equally fine.</p>
<p>Summary: If you don't know how to move, just don't. Disallowing temporaries of your class is a different concern.</p>

Q: Fill v-combobox value with an API response A: <p>Bro the error usually happens because the API response isn't a direct array. Check the response structure:</p>
<pre><code>onMounted(async () =&gt; {
  const response = await api.getBarcodeTypes()
  console.log('API Response:', response) // Debug: check actual structure

  // I think most APIs wrap the array in a 'data' property
  barcodeTypeList.value = Array.isArray(response) 
    ? response 
    : response?.data || response?.results || []
})
</code></pre>
<p>What must have happened would be either the API wraps the &quot;Many APIs return { data: [...] } instead of [...]&quot; response or if you are using Axios, the array is in response.data...or if the vuetify version might be using item-title instead of item-text.</p>
<p>Yu can just do something like:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;script setup lang=&quot;ts&quot;&gt;
onMounted(async () =&gt; {
  const data = await api.getBarcodeTypes()
  // Ensure it's always an array
  barcodeTypeList.value = Array.isArray(data) 
    ? data 
    : (data?.data || data?.results || [])
})
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>Also, if you haven't, you should also check:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Log the response to see its structure</p>
</li>
<li><p>If using Vuetify 3, change item-text to item-title</p>
</li>
<li><p>Add a loading state to avoid rendering before data loads</p>
</li>
</ol>

Q: Keyed Collection in Python? A: <p>Below is my implementation.
In my use case, I need a sequence of records where one of the fields is a primary key. It's a part of a multi-layered internal data structure -- so I want the key to be a named field, or I quickly forget what exactly it contains.</p>
<pre class="lang-py prettyprint-override"><code>import typing

T = typing.TypeVar('T', bound=typing.NamedTuple)
K = typing.TypeVar('K', bound=typing.Hashable)
class KeyedList(typing.List[T], typing.Mapping[K, T]):
    key_field: str
    def __init__(self, seq: typing.Union[typing.Iterable[T], None] = None):
        super().__init__()
        self._map = {}
        if seq is not None:
            self.__iadd__(seq)
    def _getkey(self, item: T) -&gt; K:
        return getattr(item, self.key_field)
    def __getitem__(self, key: K) -&gt; T:
        return self._map[key]
    def __contains__(self, key: K):
        return key in self._map
    def append(self, item: T) -&gt; None:
        key = self._getkey(item)
        if key in self:
            raise ValueError(f&quot;Key '{key:r}' already present&quot;)
        super().append(item)
        self._map[key] = item
    def __iadd__(self, other: typing.Iterable[T]):
        for item in other:
            self.append(item)
        return self
    def __delitem__(self, key: K):
        super().__delitem__(self[key])
        del self._map[key]
    def clear(self):
        super().__delitem__(slice(None,None))
        self._map.clear()
    def __repr__(self):
        return self.__class__.__name__ + &quot;([&quot; + &quot;, &quot;.join(repr(i) for i in self) + &quot;])&quot;
del T, K
</code></pre>
<p>The resulting hierarchical structure looks like this:</p>
<pre class="lang-py prettyprint-override"><code>class FooInfo(typing.NamedTuple):
    name: str
    some_data: int
class FooDirectory(KeyedList[FooInfo, str]):
    key_field: &quot;name&quot;
class GeneralInfo(typing.NamedTuple):
    general_id: str
    data: FooDirectory
class GeneralDirectory(KeyedList[GeneralInfo, str]):
    key_field: &quot;general_id&quot;

&lt;...&gt;
directory = GeneralDirectory()
directory.append(GeneralInfo(&quot;some_entity&quot;, FooDirectory()))
directory[&quot;some_entity&quot;].append(&quot;some_info&quot;,FooInfo())
&lt;etc&gt;
</code></pre>
